<br>
I am currently a 4th year religious studies major at the University of California, Santa Barbara.  It is the number 2 RS department in the nation behind Harvard, and even that is debatable.  I say this just to give myself from credibility.<br>
<br>
[q]Catholicism is based on governing man, as can be seen in the many pagan rituals they adopted as their own, in order to bring into the &quot;Fold&quot; those self same pagans whom participated in said rituals. Would a real religion, based merely upon spirituality, adopt the customs and practices of another religion? I dont really think so.[/q]<br>
<br>
Actually, nearly EVERY religion borrows from other traditions. It is simply the way of man-made organizations.  When placed in competition with any other system or tradition, religions will adapt, evolve, or borrow from one another.  <br>
<br>
True, the early church borrowed pagan rituals to appeal to the people of Roman provinces, but these borrowed rituals have become canonized and established.  The eucharist may be borrowed, but symbolically, you are still taking the body and blood of Christ, it doesn't matter who you got the ritual from, as long as it has meaning for you.<br>
<br>
There is no such thing as a REAL religion, there are simply religions that last longer than others.  Consider Mormonism, the fastest growing religious group in the US.  It was provably fabricated by Joseph Smith, (although the more faithful among us may still believe he received divine inspiration.)  Mormonism is considered 'fake' or a 'cult' my many protestants, but the fact remains, it is a HUGE religion, with rituals and an entire economy of spirituality that provides comfort, care, and meaning for millions.  So tell, me how does that make it 'fake'? <br>
<br>
Americans love to cite Buddhism in cases like this.  In fact, Buddhism comes from Hinduism.  Taoists considered Buddhists to be a mixed-up bunch of hippies.  The Dalai Lama was quoted as saying, &quot;if something can be demonstrably false, we will adjust our beliefs accordingly.&quot;  So because they will change their practices or adapt new rituals, does that make it a 'fake' religion?<br>
<br>
This post is getting too long, someone please flame me or someone else so I can post again.<br>
<br>
